3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates TRX/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC using the premium/discount between perpetual and spot prices. The rate is typically capped at ±2% per interval to prevent extreme movements. Payments occur automatically between long and short position holders, with zero maker fees reducing execution costs for arbitrageurs entering positions at funding payment times."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","TRX","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TRX/USDT presents strong arbitrage potential due to TRON's active DeFi ecosystem creating spot-perpetual divergences during high network activity. MEXC's zero maker fees and high leverage options up to 200x enable capital-efficient strategies, while the exchange's early listing advantage often creates unique rate patterns not found on other platforms."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"TRX/USDT on MEXC has shown cyclical funding patterns, often swinging from negative rates during market downturns to positive rates exceeding 0.1% during TRON ecosystem developments. The 8-hour interval creates less frequent but potentially larger rate movements compared to exchanges with shorter intervals. Historical data shows rates can remain persistently negative during bear markets, offering consistent income for long arbitrage positions. Peak positive rates often coincide with DeFi protocol launches or major partnerships within the TRON ecosystem."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees create optimal conditions for funding arbitrage on TRX/USDT, eliminating execution costs when opening hedged positions. The exchange's 200x leverage allows for capital-efficient strategies, requiring minimal collateral to capture funding payments. Arbitrageurs can exploit rate differentials between MEXC and other exchanges, particularly during periods of high TRX network activity when rates diverge significantly. The 8-hour payment schedule provides predictable income streams, with rates often becoming more extreme near payment times due to position adjustments."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Management"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's thinner order books for TRX/USDT can create slippage risks during large position entries, particularly during volatile periods. The exchange's questionable volume reporting raises concerns about market depth accuracy, requiring careful position sizing. Funding rate arbitrage faces basis risk if spot-perpetual convergence fails, potentially leading to losses despite positive funding payments. Limited regulatory compliance compared to tier-1 exchanges adds counterparty risk, making position monitoring and risk limits essential for sustained arbitrage operations."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are TRX/USDT funding payments made on MEXC?","answer":"MEXC calculates and pays TRX/USDT funding every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. This longer interval compared to some exchanges can result in larger rate movements and payment amounts."},{"question":"What are the fee advantages for TRX funding arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"MEXC offers zero maker fees, eliminating trading costs when opening arbitrage positions with limit orders. This fee structure makes funding rate strategies more profitable compared to exchanges charging both maker and taker fees."},{"question":"What leverage is available for TRX/USDT perpetuals on MEXC?","answer":"MEXC provides up to 200x leverage on TRX/USDT perpetuals, enabling capital-efficient funding arbitrage strategies. However, higher leverage increases liquidation risk, requiring careful margin management during volatile periods."},{"question":"How do MEXC's TRX funding rates compare to other exchanges?","answer":"MEXC's 8-hour funding intervals often create different rate patterns compared to exchanges with 1-hour or 4-hour cycles. The exchange's aggressive listing strategy and zero maker fees can lead to unique arbitrage opportunities not available elsewhere."}]}]
